-- INSTANT VIEW: Fed maintains "extended period" pledge on rates
-- 
-- Wed Dec 16, 2009 2:39pm EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/12/16/us-usa-markets-idUSTRE5BF4KB20091216

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - Voicing some optimism about a stabilizing economy, the Federal Reserve on Wednesday left its benchmark federal funds rate on hold near zero and reminded markets that it will let most of its special liquidity facilities expire by early next year. 

 Concluding a two day meeting, the Fed voted unanimously to keep benchmark borrowing costs in a zero to 0.25 percent range, and said economic conditions would likely warrant holding rates exceptionally low for "an extended period." COMMENTS: DAN COOK, SENIOR MARKET ANALYST AT IG MARKETS IN CHICAGO: "Their primary focus is still the labor market and they're not at all concerned about inflation. "By putting a firm date on the end of some of these facilities -- which will be coming up quickly -- that might put a bit of pressure on the stock market in the first part of 2010. Banks aren't going to have the liquidity to deal. "Had they not put that reminder in there about the first quarter, we would have seen that slight pop maintained. The liquidity pull back, people are looking at it and saying we're not going to get that free run that we've had in the stock market, we're not going to have all that free capital that we had previously. That will have people concerned heading into the new year." SEBASTIEN GALY, SENIOR CURRENCY STRATEGIST, BNP PARIBAS, NEW YORK: "The long-end of yield curve will probably pick up on this, and that will help dollar-yen shoot higher toward 90. By guaranteeing liquidity, the Fed encourages risk-taking and risky assets are being bought, but that's starting to boost the dollar-yen now. It's the most sensitive pair to the yield curve, and since the Fed is still trying to inflate assets as much as they can, this is the right trade. The market not sure whether it makes much sense to buy euro-dollar on dips now or whether long euro trades make sense given the quality of